Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pop the @cauliflower florets{300%g} onto a #baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{drizzle}. Season with @salt{} and sprinkle on the @Thai style spice blend{1%packet} (add less if you don't like heat). Use your hands to rub the seasoning all over. Spread out in a single layer and roast until soft and golden, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a #tight-fitting lid{}. Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp}, cover with the lid and bring to the boil on medium-high heat. Once boiling, turn the heat down to its lowest setting. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

While the rice cooks, halve the @green pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 2cm chunks. Trim the @pak choi{1}, then separate the leaves. Quarter each leaf widthways into roughly 2cm chunks. Chop the @baby corn{60%g} into 2cm thick rounds. Zest then cut the @lime{1/2} into wedges. Roughly chop the @coriander{1 bunch}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Heat a splash of oil in a #large frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Stir-fry the pepper and baby corn until beginning to soften and colour, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir in the @yellow Thai style paste{45%g} to coat and cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the pak choi along with the @coconut milk{200%ml} and the @water for the sauce{75%ml}. Bring to the boil then turn the heat to medium-low.

Let the curry simmer until the baby corn is tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. When the cauliflower is ready, add it to the curry and stir through. Remove from the heat and stir in the @soy sauce{12.5%ml}. Squeeze in some lime juice. Taste and add more salt, pepper and lime juice if needed. Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir in the lime zest and half the coriander.

Share the rice between your #bowls{} and top with the curry. Finish with a sprinkle of the remaining coriander. Serve the remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over. Enjoy!

> MOD: If you've added prawns to your curry, add to the sauce once you've brought it to the boil and simmer for 4-5 mins as specified in step 5. The @?king prawns{150%g} are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Remove water and prawns if you are using them, then add @?king prawns{150%g} to the pan with the yellow Thai style paste and cook until pink, about 4-5 minutes before adding coconut milk.